## 2. Calibration System

### Architecture

The calibration system is split into two files:

| File | Runs where | Purpose |
|---|---|---|
| `src/lib/calibration.ts` | Build-time (Node) | Math helpers, type definitions |
| `src/scripts/calibration-engine.ts` | Browser (ES module) | DPI detection, localStorage, DOM events |

### The Math

```
pixels_per_mm = DPI / 25.4
object_width_px = widthMm * pixels_per_mm
```

For a 24.26 mm coin at 96 DPI: `24.26 × (96 / 25.4) = 91.7 px`

### Three Calibration Methods

#### Method 1: Credit Card (Most Accurate — Default)
- Standard credit card is **85.60 mm × 53.98 mm** (ISO/IEC 7810 ID-1)
- User places physical card on screen and drags a guide box to match
- DPI is computed from the guide's pixel width: `dpi = (guidePx / 85.60) * 25.4`
- **Why first**: Nearly everyone has a credit card. Zero additional input needed.

#### Method 2: Known Object / Coin
- Dropdown of known objects (US Quarter = 24.26 mm, Euro = 23.25 mm, etc.)
- Same drag-to-match UI as Method 1 but for circular coins
- Useful when users don't have a card handy

#### Method 3: Monitor Diagonal (Fallback)
- User enters their monitor's diagonal size in inches
- Browser reads `screen.width` × `screen.height` in CSS pixels
- DPI = `√(screen.width² + screen.height²) / diagonalInches`
- Least accurate due to HiDPI scaling, but widely applicable

### Calibration State Machine

```typescript
// State stored in localStorage key: "actualsize:calibration"
interface CalibrationState {
  dpi: number;
  method: "credit-card" | "coin" | "monitor" | "default";
  calibratedAt: string;   // ISO timestamp
  confidence: "high" | "medium" | "low";
}

// Default when no calibration exists
const DEFAULT_STATE: CalibrationState = {
  dpi: 96,
  method: "default",
  calibratedAt: new Date().toISOString(),
  confidence: "low",
};
```

### The CSS Variable Bridge (Key Architectural Decision)

When calibration completes, the engine does **one single DOM write**:

```typescript
document.documentElement.style.setProperty('--dpi', String(newDPI));
```

This single write instantly reflows **every** `ActualSizeViewer` on the page via CSS `calc()`. No React state, no component re-renders, no event listeners in each object component. This is the entire "reactivity" of the system.

### Calibration Event

```typescript
// Dispatched on window after DPI is updated
window.dispatchEvent(new CustomEvent('calibration:updated', {
  detail: { dpi: number, method: string, confidence: string }
}));
```

The `CalibrationBar` listens to this to update its UI label ("Calibrated ✓").

